The paper discusses the use of deep neural networks (DNNs) in various domains, including medical diagnosis, security, and autonomous driving, which are all related to machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The focus of the paper is on Bayesian deep networks, which are a type of deep neural network, and the development of a new method called MC-DropConnect to approximate Bayesian inference for DNNs. This makes it likely that the paper falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the use of the proposed method for classification and semantic segmentation tasks, which are related to computer vision (cs.CV). Additionally, the paper mentions the importance of safety in sensitive applications, which suggests that it may also fall under the category of systems and control (cs.SY). Finally, the paper discusses the validation of the proposed algorithm on multiple network architectures and datasets, which suggests that it may also fall under the category of neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE).
